Right, this is the sunk cost fallacy. I agree with this one, as it pushes the same point. She does not want to throw away this relationship, this past time together. How could her past decisions to be with him be wrong? Did she not read him correctly? No, surely she did, it's just that he needs more time. Yes. Just another year.\
Either way, the real reason she subscribed to her way of thinking, why the student subscribes to the University, is to defend against change. To protect her 'true self.' It's funny, even after hundreds of years of liberalism and allowing anyone to do anything, we still choose to lock ourselves in cages. Consider Tom, the University student. Tom wakes up in the morning, and goes to class. Tom gets lunch after class, and hangs out with a buddy. Tom goes to his last class of the day, and studies and does tomorrow's homework for a bit. Then Tom gets dinner, and after, Tom might watch Netflix, or play some video games. Then, Tom scrolls on his phone or masturbates before bed. He then sleeps, and lives the same day for a lifetime.\
I'm sure you know Tom. I will call this the infinite work-goon cycle, AKA, the pathway to being a cog. Tom subscribes to this way of living life because he sees it everyone doing it, and social proof says: if everyone is doing something, it's probably ok. So he just does what is ok. He does not venture beyond his classes. He takes just enough credits for his day-to-day to have a productive feeling. He numbs his boredom with quick-shot stimulation, a quick scroll between classes, on the bus ride, or every time his friend has to respond to a message or lose the conversation for longer than 2 seconds. The point is, Tom subscribes to this model because he expects everything will go well, and that he does not have to change. He does not have to think. No one, not even himself, will question him, he's so perfectly average. He trades his agency for comfort, it's easier to make decisions if you walk into a box.\
Why is this cage so awful? Why do most people fall into this shitty cage, this model? It's because models fueled by social proof and feigning ignorance are most commonly adapted to everyone. For everyone to like something, it must have a low bar of entry. Everyone 'likes' Keanu Reeves. Cause he likes dogs. Come on man, everyone likes dogs.\
Guess what? It's all about having a fallback. Let's play the blame game, where the prize is stagnation and the entry ticket is your soul! Why do these people so desperately want to shove the blame elsewhere? It is because they want to be seen as the victim, they don't want to damage their self image. Because it wasn't on them - no, they are perfect - it was someone else hindering them. Oh, he treated me so poorly, but I was so charitable, I gave him another chance in the marriage! Woman, you could've divorced him years prior. But you're scared, aren't you? You're scared people will see you as rash, see you as someone who is immature, someone who would throw away a family life for herself. Someone selfish! No, she couldn't be all that. So without a choice, she is 'charitable.' It's other's views of her FOMO that cause her to stay more than her own FOMO. She says it's for her FOMO because it's understandable for others. Isn't that fascinating?\
For Tom? When his life turns to a deadpan 9-5 while his wife gets orgasms from ChatGPT smut? He'll blame the system. I was fooled! Everyone else was doing the same thing, I got tricked! He will cry, and everyone else who also got 'scammed' will get together in a circle in a mildewy jizz-stained basement and jerk each other off, because it couldn't possibly be their fault they are like this. "Oh, woe, the system has failed us!" Did you read the fine print? Did you read at all? Seriously.\
Can you imagine the student who subscribes to the University model - get a good GPA, good internships = job - and doesn't get a job? He will blame the market. He will blame the University. "It was promised to me!", he will scream into r/thejokerwasright. Everyone blames the job market. "It's just so rough." But if you were good and dedicated enough, you'd get a job. People don't owe you anything if you aren't worth the money. People say this because they don't want the fact that they didn't get a job to be on their own fault. No, it is on the big evil job market instead. It should be handed to me on a silver platter! If the competency required for a job you want goes up, then it is on you to become that competent.\
This is also why the university student is so worried about not getting a summer internship. The model clearly states that, if you get good internships and good grades, then you will get a job. The student understands that, and it's up to them in order to satisfy the model. So if they don't get the internship, don't get the research, then they can't push any future disappointments onto the model being wrong. They didn't satisfy the blueprint, after all. It's on them. People will still find a way to blame it on external things, though: the internship season that year was so hard! The hiring person was so rough! Whatever. The bottom line is, they are stressed if they don't get an internship because then they have to A. Switch models or B. Accept that they did not fulfill the model, and that the blame is on them.\
