Excuses, excuses, excuses. Complaining about things is also a defense of your character. Oh man, my CS teacher is just such a rough grader translates directly to: I'm smart, it's his fault I'm doing poorly. Sometimes there are annoying graders. But no matter how you phrase it, you are defending your fake 'character' with this statement. You could also be trying to bolster your character; "Oh man, this teacher is such a harsh grader." Then when they ask, you say like "Oh I only got like a 94\'85" This is reverse, you want your character to have high standards in terms of grades, and to show that despite the harsh grading you still persevered. One wants to appear smart, one wants to not be seen as dumb.\
Let me tell you a story. There is a guy called James, and James has a friend named Carl. Carl is James's old boss at their auto dealer. James recently moved jobs, to a different dealership. Carl calls James sometimes for coffee, and every time they see each other, Carl just complains infinitely to James. Carl is a real bum, drinks alcohol, cheats on his wife, and tells James about how it's his wife's fault. But James stays, and listens. James hates every minute of it, but he listens.\
James goes home and talks to his wife about it, complaining about Carl and how he hates that he has to hang out with him. His wife says the thing we are all thinking: "Just stop talking to Carl." James is stunned. He quickly retorts with, "Oh, but I wish I could, I owe him a favor and also I want to keep my eye open for any future job positions with him incase this one goes sour." These are fake reasons which he thought of with a term I am coining "ass wipage." Ok maybe we can call it hindsight reasoning, but the terms are synonymous. He is caught with his pants down, she is asking why he doesn't man up and stop talking to him, so he spins up some fake reasons. He could really believe these reasons, too, but they are absolutely not the driving reason. The driving reason is that he wants someone to complain about, someone to act as a shield before the truth that he is upset about himself. He wants to believe that he is upset about himself because he had to spend mental energy on his ex-boss's venting.\
I just wanted to write this to point out things that are bad. But I realize I should close with something good. Models are absolutely useful. You need them to learn, to adapt, to grow. The lesson here is to not get too hung up on your internal idea of yourself. I will share my strategy now, I convince myself to be so cocky and well thought that I think that I am capable of anything. Am I really? Likely not. But I'm sure it's more productive for me to think that I could do anything than if I thought I couldn't do anything, or if I was anxious about it. With one of these mindsets, I will try everything once. With the other, I would do one thing, do it well, and never do anything else out of fear. Don't spend your life building your minifigure.\
